<p>One joule is also equivalent to any of the following:<sup id="cite&#95;ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>7<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The work required to move an <a href="/wiki/Electric_charge" title="Electric charge">electric charge</a> of one <a href="/wiki/Coulomb" title="Coulomb">coulomb</a> through an <a href="/wiki/Voltage" title="Voltage">electrical potential difference</a> of one volt, or one coulomb-volt (C⋅V). This relationship can be used to define the volt.</li>
<li>The work required to produce one watt of <a href="/wiki/Power_(physics)" title="Power (physics)">power</a> for one second, or one watt-second (W⋅s) (compare <a href="/wiki/Kilowatt-hour" title="Kilowatt-hour">kilowatt-hour</a>, which is 3.6 megajoules). This relationship can be used to define the watt.</li></ul>
<p>The joule is named after <a href="/wiki/James_Prescott_Joule" title="James Prescott Joule">James Prescott Joule</a>. As with every <a href="/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title="International System of Units">SI</a> unit named after a person, its symbol starts with an <a href="/wiki/Upper_case" class="mw-redirect" title="Upper case">upper case</a> letter (J), but when written in full, it follows the rules for capitalisation of a <a href="/wiki/Common_noun" class="mw-redirect" title="Common noun">common noun</a>; i.e., <i>joule</i> becomes capitalised at the beginning of a sentence and in titles but is otherwise in lower case.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>8<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
